==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ogle
<hw>O"gle</hw> <pr>(⟦omac⟧g'l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Ogled</conjf> <pr>(⟦omac⟧g'ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Ogling</conjf>
<pr>(⟦omac⟧"gl⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From a Dutch word
corresponding to G. <ets>⟦aum⟧ugeln</ets> to ogle, fr. <ets>auge</ets>
eye; cf. D. <ets>ooglonken</ets> to ogle, OD. <ets>oogen</ets> to cast
sheep's eyes upon, <ets>ooge</ets> eye. See <er>Eye</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To view or look at with side glances, as in fondness,
or with a design to attract notice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>ogling</qex> all their audience, ere they speak.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To stare at conspicuously or
impertinently.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ogle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ogle
<hw>O"gle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An amorous side glance or look.</def>
<rj><au>Byron.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ogler</ent>⟦br⟧
